            "id": "dd00988dba8e4530b7796",
            "questionText": "Consider an electric guitar pickup with a coil of 500 turns wrapped around a magnet. A steel string vibrates above the pickup, causing the magnetic flux through the coil to change. Suppose the area of the coil is $!$2 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{m}^2$!$ and the magnetic field near the string varies as $!$B(t) = 0.05 \\cos(2\\pi f t)$!$ Tesla, where $!$f = 440 \\mathrm{Hz}$!$ is the frequency of the vibrating string. Calculate the generator peak voltage induced in the coil due to the changing magnetic flux.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "02935b888b4b450387331",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recalling the concept of magnetic flux. Identify the correct formula that relates magnetic flux to the magnetic field and the area of the coil, considering the orientation angle.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a36f52e3-bc9a-40d7-86cc-f5525829e75d"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Phi = BA\\cos\\theta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Phi = NBA$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Phi = \\frac{B}{A}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "b7e28aaf6ee54b9fac7d6",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, using the values provided, calculate the magnetic flux through one turn of the coil. Remember to consider that the cosine factor reaches its maximum value when the magnetic field is aligned with the area normal.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1e-5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "Wb",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a36f52e3-bc9a-40d7-86cc-f5525829e75d"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "7818d017dd1d48f582475",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the flux per turn, determine the total flux linkage by considering all 500 turns of the coil. Multiply the flux per turn by the number of turns.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "5e-3"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "Wb",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "43ab751d-5780-4129-9908-e52dacbdf1d8",
                        "a36f52e3-bc9a-40d7-86cc-f5525829e75d"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "bd550e3d8bbb4d968f504",
                    "stepText": "To connect the change in flux linkage to the generated voltage, recall Faraday's Law. Please select the correct formula that relates the induced electromotive force (emf) to the time derivative of the flux linkage.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "01f9d96a-7639-4028-8921-a8d295d26596"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = -N\\frac{\\Delta\\Phi}{\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = -\\frac{\\Delta\\Phi}{\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\epsilon = N\\frac{\\Delta\\Phi}{\\Delta t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d1fa5195df5244a9971c6",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use the relationship for the peak generator voltage. The peak induced emf is given by multiplying the number of turns, the amplitude of the magnetic field, the coil area, and the angular frequency. Calculate this peak voltage using $!$N (B_{0})(2\\pi f)(A)$!$. Plug in the provided numbers to get the final answer.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
